part -2 of the activity-1:
explore the following commands:
1)whoami:
description:
whoami - print effective user name
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ whoami
raakin
remarks:The whoami command in Linux outputs the username of the current user logged into the session, helping to identify the effective user running the command or script.

-------------------------------------------------------------------
2)pwd:
description:
   pwd - print name of current/working directory
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ pwd
/home/raakin
remarks:The pwd command in Linux stands for "print working directory" and it displays the absolute path of the current directory the user is working in, starting from the root directory (/)

--------------------------------------------------------------------
3)cd:
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ cd Pictures
raakin@ubuntu-25:~/Pictures$ pwd
/home/raakin/Pictures
remarks:
The cd command in Linux is used to change the current working directory to a specified directory; if used without any argument, it takes the user to their home directory.

-------------------------------------------------------------------
3)cd /:
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ cd Pictures
raakin@ubuntu-25:~/Pictures$ cd /
raakin@ubuntu-25:/$ 
remark:
The command cd / in Linux changes the current directory to the root directory, which is the top-level directory in the filesystem hierarchy.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
4)cd <space>:
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ cd Pictures
raakin@ubuntu-25:~/Pictures$ cd 
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ 
remark:
 running cd alone or with no arguments will take the user to their home directory.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
5)cd <space> <path>
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ cd "Pictures"
raakin@ubuntu-25:~/Pictures$ 
remark:
When using the cd command in Linux followed by a space and then a directory path (e.g., cd <space><path>), it changes the current directory to the given path.
If the path contains spaces, it must be enclosed in quotes or have spaces escaped with a backslash (\) for the command to work correctly. 

----------------------------------------------------------------------
